TY  - JOUR
T1  - Board Composition from Adolescence to Maturity: A Multitheoretic View
AU  - Lynall, Matthew D.
AU  - Golden, Brian R.
AU  - Hillman, Amy J.
Y1  - 2003/07/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2003.10196743
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2003.10196743
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 416
EP  - 431
VL  - 28
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We develop theory to show how board composition and, consequently, firm performance are a reflection of both the firm's life cycle stage and the relative power of the CEO and external financiers at the time of founding. This theory provides insight into the predictive validity of agency, resource dependence, institutional, and social network theories. We also argue that boards are subject to path dependency, and, thus, board composition is likely to persist over time.
AB  - We develop theory to show how board composition and, consequently, firm performance are a reflection of both the firm's life cycle stage and the relative power of the CEO and external financiers at the time of founding. This theory provides insight into the predictive validity of agency, resource dependence, institutional, and social network theories. We also argue that boards are subject to path dependency, and, thus, board composition is likely to persist over time.
