TY  - JOUR
T1  - Mutual Forbearance: The Role of Intrafirm Integration and Rewards
AU  - Golden, Brian R.
AU  - Ma, Hao
Y1  - 2003/07/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2003.10196787
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2003.10196787
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 479
EP  - 493
VL  - 28
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Despite increasing attention given to mutual forbearance strategies (MFS), researchers have virtually ignored the internal arrangements necessary for their implementation. We argue that the design of the mutual forbearance competitor may pose some unique implementation challenges for the firm, theorize about the administrative mechanisms that we expect to characterize firms implementing MFS, and suggest that, to the extent that future researchers do not model the qualities theoretically necessary to implement MFS, the full competitive consequences of MFS will not be appreciated.
AB  - Despite increasing attention given to mutual forbearance strategies (MFS), researchers have virtually ignored the internal arrangements necessary for their implementation. We argue that the design of the mutual forbearance competitor may pose some unique implementation challenges for the firm, theorize about the administrative mechanisms that we expect to characterize firms implementing MFS, and suggest that, to the extent that future researchers do not model the qualities theoretically necessary to implement MFS, the full competitive consequences of MFS will not be appreciated.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2003.10196787
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2003.10196787
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Influencing Initial Public Offering Investors with Prestige: Signaling with Board Structures
AU  - Certo, S. Trevis
Y1  - 2003/07/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2003.10196754
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2003.10196754
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 432
EP  - 446
VL  - 28
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - I describe how board structures influence the decision-making processes that investors use when purchasing shares of firms undertaking initial public offerings (IPOs). IPO firms are relatively unknown to investors and suffer from a liability of market newness. I rely on signaling theory, institutional theory, and sociological research on prestige to suggest that investor perceptions of board prestige signal organizational legitimacy, thereby reducing the liability of market newness and improving IPO firm stock performance. I also propose that the characteristics of investors, namely prestige, influence their perceptions of board prestige.
AB  - I describe how board structures influence the decision-making processes that investors use when purchasing shares of firms undertaking initial public offerings (IPOs). IPO firms are relatively unknown to investors and suffer from a liability of market newness. I rely on signaling theory, institutional theory, and sociological research on prestige to suggest that investor perceptions of board prestige signal organizational legitimacy, thereby reducing the liability of market newness and improving IPO firm stock performance. I also propose that the characteristics of investors, namely prestige, influence their perceptions of board prestige.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2003.10196754
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2003.10196754
Y2  - 2026/04/24
